# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clock
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The main advantage of a decimal time system is that, since the base used to divide the time is the same as the one used to represent it, the representation of hours, minutes and seconds can be handled as a unified value.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Therefore, it becomes simpler to interpret a timestamp and to perform conversions.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] For instance, 1h23m45s is 1 decimal hour, 23 decimal minutes, and 45 decimal seconds, or 1.2345 decimal hours, or 123.45 decimal minutes or 12345 decimal seconds; 3 hours is 300 minutes or 30,000 seconds.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] It also adjusts well to digital time representation using epochs, in that the internal time representation can be used directly both for computation and for user-facing display.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The **decans** are 36 groups of stars (small constellations) used in the ancient Egyptian astronomy to conveniently divide the 360 degree ecliptic into 36 parts of 10 degrees.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] A ten-day period between the rising of two consecutive decans is a decade.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] There were 36 decades (36 × 10 = 360 days), plus five added days to compose the 365 days of a solar based year.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Decimal time was used in China throughout most of its history alongside duodecimal time.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The midnight-to-midnight day was divided both into 12 double hours (traditional Chinese: 時辰; simplified Chinese: 时辰; pinyin: *shí chén*) and also into 10 shi / 100 *ke* (Chinese: 刻; pinyin: *kè*) by the 1st millennium BC.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Other numbers of *ke* per day were used during three short periods: 120 *ke* from 5 to 3 BC, 96 *ke* from AD 507 to 544, and 108 *ke* from 544 to 565.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Several of the roughly 50 Chinese calendars also divided each *ke* into 100 *fen*, although others divided each *ke* into 60 *fen*.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In 1280, the *Shoushi* (Season Granting) calendar further subdivided each *fen* into 100 *miao*, creating a complete decimal time system of 100 *ke*, 100 *fen* and 100 *miao*.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Chinese decimal time ceased to be used in 1645 when the Shíxiàn calendar, based on European astronomy and brought to China by the Jesuits, adopted 96 *ke* per day alongside 12 double hours, making each *ke* exactly one-quarter hour.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Gēng (更) is a time signal given by drum or gong.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The character for gēng 更, literally meaning "rotation" or "watch", comes from the rotation of watchmen sounding these signals.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The first gēng theoretically comes at sundown, but was standardized to fall at 19:12.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The time between each gēng is 1⁄10 of a day, making a gēng 2.4 hours long (2 hours 24 minutes).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] As a 10-part system, the gēng are strongly associated with the 10 celestial stems, especially since the stems are used to count off the gēng during the night in Chinese literature.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] As early as the Bronze-Age Xia dynasty, days were grouped into ten-day weeks known as xún (旬).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The first 10 days were the early xún (上旬), the middle 10 the mid xún (中旬), and the last nine or 10 days were the late xún (下旬).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Japan adopted this pattern, with 10-day-weeks known as jun (旬).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] , the day, the hour, etc. would be from tens into tens.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] , of the day into twenty-four hours, the hour into sixty minutes, etc.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In 1788, Claude Boniface Collignon proposed dividing the day into 10 hours or 1,000 minutes, each new hour into 100 minutes, each new minute into 1,000 seconds, and each new second into 1,000 *tierces* (older French for "third").
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The distance the twilight zone travels in one such *tierce* at the equator, which would be one-billionth of the circumference of the earth, would be a new unit of length, provisionally called a half-handbreadth, equal to four modern centimetres.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Further, the new *tierce* would be divided into 1,000 *quatierces*, which he called "microscopic points of time".
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] He also suggested a week of 10 days and dividing the year into 10 "solar months".
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Decimal time was officially introduced during the French Revolution.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Jean-Charles de Borda made a proposal for decimal time on 5 November 1792.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] , each part into ten others, so on until the smallest measurable portion of the duration.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Thus, midnight was called *dix heures* ("ten hours"*)*, noon was called *cinq heures* ("five hours"), etc.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The colon (:) was not yet in use as a unit separator for standard times, and is used for non-decimal bases.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The French decimal separator is the comma (,), while the period (.), or "point", is used in English.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Units were either written out in full, or abbreviated.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Thus, five hours eighty three minutes decimal might be written as 5 h.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Even today, "h" is commonly used in France to separate hours and minutes of 24-hour time, instead of a colon, such as 14h00.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Midnight was represented in civil records as "ten hours".
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Times between midnight and the first decimal hour were written without hours, so 1:00 am, or 0.41 decimal hours, was written as "four décimes" or "forty-one minutes".
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] 2:00 am (0.8333) was written as "eight décimes", "eighty-three minutes", or even "eighty-three minutes thirty-three seconds".
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] As with duodecimal time, decimal time was represented according to true solar time, rather than mean time, with noon being marked when the sun reached its highest point locally, which varied at different locations, and throughout the year.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Sometimes in official records, decimal hours were divided into tenths, or *décimes*, instead of minutes.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] One *décime* is equal to 10 decimal minutes, which is nearly equal to a quarter-hour (15 minutes) in standard time.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Thus, "five hours two décimes" equals 5.2 decimal hours, roughly 12:30 p.m. in standard time.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] One hundredth of a decimal second was a decimal *tierce*.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In spite of this, decimal time was used in many cities, including Marseille and Toulouse, where a decimal clock with just an hour hand was on the front of the Capitole for five years.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In some places, decimal time was used to record certificates of births, marriages, and deaths until the end of Year VIII (September 1800).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] On the Palace of the Tuileries in Paris, two of the four clock faces displayed decimal time until at least 1801.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The mathematician and astronomer Pierre-Simon Laplace had a decimal watch made for him, and used decimal time in his work, in the form of fractional days.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The start of each year was determined according to the day of the autumnal equinox, in relation to true or apparent solar time at the Paris Observatory.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In designing the new metric system, the intent was to replace all the various units of different bases with a small number of standard decimal units.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] This was to include units for length, weight, area, liquid capacity, volume, and money.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Initially the traditional second of time equal to 1/86400 day was proposed as the base of the metric system, but this was changed in 1791 to base the meter on a decimal division of a measurement of the Earth, instead.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Early drafts of the metric system published in 1793 included the new decimal divisions of the day included with the Republican calendar, and some of the same individuals were involved with both projects.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] On March 28, 1794, Joseph-Louis Lagrange proposed to the Commission for Republican Weights and Measures on dividing the day into 10 decidays and 100 centidays, which would be expressed together as two digits, counting periods of 14 minutes and 24 seconds since midnight, nearly a quarter hour.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] This would be displayed by one hand on watches.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Another hand would display 100 divisions of a centiday, which is 1/10,000 day, or 8.64 seconds.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] A third hand on a smaller dial would further divide these into 10, which would be 1/100,000 day, or 864 milliseconds, slightly less than a whole second.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] He suggested the deciday and centiday be used together to represent the time of day, such as "4 and 5", "4/5", or simply "45".
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] For others, there would be 50 decimal minutes per decimal hour, and 100 decimal seconds per decimal minute.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] His new hours, minutes, and seconds would thus be more similar to the old units.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] 3) This habit would be further consolidated by the fear of confusion.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] 5) Finally, citizens and watchmakers would be infinitely dismayed, some to change their watches, others to lose the ability to sell those that are already made.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] This truth is acquired by the result of the contest which took place recently, under the decree on watchmaking movements.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] But by asking that the decimal division of the day is not a condition of rigor, there is no disagreement that there are several circumstances where it has advantages.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] We know that in several objects of the Navy service, in astronomical or trigonometric calculations, and for delicate experiments, the decimal division of time is more convenient.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] It will therefore be good to reserve it for these cases, until the use can spread more generally, which will happen by itself imperceptibly.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Thus, the law of 18 Germinal An III (April 7, 1795) establishing the metric system, rather than including metric units for time, repealed the mandatory use of decimal time, although its use continued for a number of years in some places.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] As predicted, it was quickly found to be useful by astronomers, who still use it in the form of fractional days.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Carl Friedrich Gauss recommended the ephemeris second as a metric base unit for time interval in 1832, which eventually became the atomic second in the International System.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] However, for longer periods of time interval, the old non-decimal units were approved for use.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] That the Conference expresses the hope that the technical studies designed to regulate and extend the application of the decimal system to the division of angular space and of time shall be resumed, so as to permit the extension of this application to all cases in which it presents real advantages.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In the 1890s, Joseph Charles François de Rey-Pailhade, president of the Toulouse Geographical Society, proposed dividing the day into 100 parts, called *cés*, equal to 14.4 standard minutes, and each divided into 10 *decicés*, 100 *centicés*, etc.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The Toulouse Chamber of Commerce adopted a resolution supporting his proposal in April 1897.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Although widely published, the proposal received little backing.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The French made another attempt at the decimalization of time in 1897, when the *Commission de décimalisation du temps* was created by the Bureau des Longitudes, with the mathematician Henri Poincaré as secretary.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The commission adopted a compromise, originally proposed by Henri de Sarrauton of the Oran Geographical Society, of retaining the 24-hour day, but dividing each hour into 100 decimal minutes, and each minute into 100 seconds.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The plan did not gain acceptance and was abandoned in 1900.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Although Swatch did not specify units smaller than one .beat, third party implementations extended the standard by adding "centibeats" or "sub-beats", for extended precision: @248.00.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Each "centibeat" was a hundredth of a .beat and was therefore equal to one French decimal second (0.864 seconds).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] When using .beats and centibeats, Swatch Internet Time divided the day into 1,000 French decimal minutes and each decimal minute into 100 decimal seconds.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] So 9pm was 21:00:00 in standard time and @875.00 in extended Swatch Internet Time.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Swatch no longer markets digital watches with Internet Time.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] There are exactly 86,400 standard seconds (see SI for the current definition of the standard second) in a standard day, but in the French decimal time system there were 100,000 decimal seconds in the day; thus, the decimal second was 13.6% shorter than its standard counterpart.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Another common type of decimal time is decimal hours.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In 1896, Henri de Sarrauton of the Oran Geographical Society proposed dividing the 24 hours of the day each into 100 decimal minutes, and each minute into 100 decimal seconds.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Although endorsed by the Bureau des Longitudes, this proposal failed, but using decimal fractions of an hour to represent the time of day instead of minutes has become common.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Decimal hours are frequently used in accounting for payrolls and hourly billing.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Time clocks typically record the time of day in tenths or hundredths of an hour.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] For instance, 08:30 would be recorded as 08.50.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] This is intended to make accounting easier by eliminating the need to convert between minutes and hours.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] For aviation purposes, where it is common to add times in an already complicated environment, time tracking is simplified by recording decimal fractions of hours.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] For instance, instead of adding 1:36 to 2:36, getting 3:72 and converting it to 4:12, one would add 1.6 to 2.6 and get 4.2 hours.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The time of day is sometimes represented as a decimal fraction of a day in science and computers.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Standard 24-hour time is converted into a fractional day by dividing the number of hours elapsed since midnight by 24 to make a decimal fraction.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] As many decimal places may be used as required for precision, so 0.5 d = 0.500000 d.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Fractional days are often calculated in UTC or TT, although Julian Dates use pre-1925 astronomical date/time (each date began at noon = ".0") and Microsoft Excel uses the local time zone of the computer.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Using fractional days reduces the number of units in time calculations from four (days, hours, minutes, seconds) to just one (days).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Fractional days have been used by astronomers ever since.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Fractional days are commonly used to express epochs of orbital elements.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The decimal fraction is usually added to the calendar date or Julian day for natural objects, or to the ordinal date for artificial satellites in two-line elements.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The second is the International System of Units (SI) unit of time duration.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] It is also the standard single-unit time representation in many programming languages, most notably C, and part of UNIX/POSIX standards used by Linux, Mac OS X, etc.; to convert fractional days to fractional seconds, multiply the number by 86400.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Fractional seconds are represented as milliseconds (ms), microseconds (μs) or nanoseconds (ns).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Absolute times are usually represented relative to 1 January 1970, at midnight UT.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Other systems may use a different zero point (like Unix time).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In principle, time spans greater than one second may be given in units such as kiloseconds (ks), megaseconds (Ms), gigaseconds (Gs), and so on.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Occasionally, these units can be found in technical literature, but traditional units like minutes, hours, days and years are much more common.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] It is possible to specify the time of day as the number of kiloseconds of elapsed time since midnight.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Thus, instead of saying 3:45 p.m. one could say (time of day) 56.7 ks.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] There are exactly 86.4 ks in one day (each kilosecond being equivalent to 16 minutes and 40 seconds worth of conventional time).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] However, this nomenclature is rarely used in practice.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Scientists often record time as decimal.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] For example, decimal days divide the day into 10 equal parts, and decimal years divide the year into 10 equal parts.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Decimals are easier to plot than both (a) minutes and seconds, which uses the sexagesimal numbering system, (b) hours, months and days, which has irregular month lengths.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In astronomy, the so-called Julian day uses decimal days centered on Greenwich noon.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Since there are 60 seconds in a minute, a tenth part represents ⁠60/10⁠ = 6 seconds.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Since there are 60 minutes in an hour, a tenth part represents ⁠60/10⁠ = 6 minutes.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Since there are 24 hours in a day, a tenth part represents ⁠24/10⁠ = 2.4 hours (2 hours and 24 minutes).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Since there are about 365 days in a year, there are about ⁠365/10⁠ = 36.5 days in a tenth of a year.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Hence the year 2020.5 represents the day 2 July 2020.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] More exactly, a "Julian year" is approximately 365.25 days long, so a tenth of the year is 36.525 days (36 days, 12 hours, 36 minutes).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] These values, based on the Julian year, are most likely to be those used in astronomy and related sciences.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] A Gregorian year, which takes into account the 100 vs.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] 400 leap year exception rule of the Gregorian calendar, is 365.2425 days (the average length of a year over a 400–year cycle), resulting in 0.1 years being a period of 36.52425 days (3155695.2 seconds; 36 days, 12 hours, 34 minutes, 55.2 seconds).
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Many people have proposed variations of decimal time, dividing the day into different numbers of units and subunits with different names.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Some decimal time proposals are based upon alternate units of metric time.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The difference between metric time and decimal time is that metric time defines units for measuring time interval, as measured with a stopwatch, and decimal time defines the time of day, as measured by a clock.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Just as standard time uses the metric time unit of the second as its basis, proposed decimal time scales may use alternative metric units.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] In the fictional *Star Trek* universe, each stardate increment represents one milliyear, with 78 years in 2401, counted from 2323.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] The decimal represents a fractional day.
[src:clock/10-hour-clock] Thus, stardates are a composition of two types of decimal time.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The **12-hour clock** is a time convention in which the 24 hours of the day are divided into two periods: **a.m.** (from Latin ***ante meridiem***, translating to "before midday") and **p.m.** (from Latin ***post meridiem***, translating to "after midday").
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock has been developed since the second millennium BC and reached its modern form in the 16th century.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour time convention is common in several English-speaking nations and former British colonies, as well as a few other countries.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In English-speaking countries: "12 p.m." usually indicates noon, while "12 a.m." means midnight, but the reverse convention has also been used (see § Confusion at noon and midnight).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The natural day-and-night division of a calendar day forms the fundamental basis as to why each day is split into two cycles.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Originally there were two cycles: one cycle which could be tracked by the position of the Sun (day), followed by one cycle which could be tracked by the Moon and stars (night).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This eventually evolved into the two 12-hour periods which are used today, one called "a.m." starting at midnight and another called "p.m." starting at noon.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock can be traced back as far as Mesopotamia and ancient Egypt.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Both an Egyptian sundial for daytime use and an Egyptian water clock for night-time use were found in the tomb of Pharaoh Amenhotep I.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] 1500 BC, these clocks divided their respective times of use into 12 hours each.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The ancient Romans also used a 12-hour clock: daylight and nighttime were each divided into 12 equal intervals (of varying duration according to the season).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The nighttime hours were grouped into four *watches* (*vigiliae*).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The first mechanical clocks in the 14th century, if they had dials at all, showed all 24 hours using the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by astronomers' familiarity with the astrolabe and sundial and by their desire to model the Earth's apparent motion around the Sun.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In Northern Europe these dials generally used the 12-hour numbering scheme in Roman numerals but showed both *a.m.* and *p.m.* periods in sequence.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This is known as the double-XII system and can be seen on many surviving clock faces, such as those at Wells and Exeter.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Elsewhere in Europe, numbering was more likely to be based on the 24-hour system (I to XXIV).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock was used throughout the British Empire.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] During the 15th and 16th centuries, the 12-hour analog dial and time system gradually became established as standard throughout Northern Europe for general public use.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The 24-hour analog dial was reserved for more specialized applications, such as astronomical clocks and chronometers.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Most analog clocks and watches today use the 12-hour dial, on which the shorter hour hand rotates once every 12 hours and twice in one day.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Some analog clock dials have an inner ring of numbers along with the standard 1-to-12 numbered ring.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The number 12 is paired either with a 00 or a 24, while the numbers 1 through 11 are paired with the numbers 13 through 23, respectively.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This modification allows the clock to also be read in 24-hour notation.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This kind of 12-hour clock can be found in countries where the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Even in those countries where the 12-hour clock is predominant, there are frequently contexts (such as science, medicine, the military or transport) in which the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In most countries, however, the 24-hour clock is the standard system used, especially in writing.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Some nations in Europe and Latin America use a combination of the two, preferring the 12-hour system in colloquial speech but using the 24-hour system in written form and in formal contexts.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock in speech often uses phrases such as*... in the morning*,*... in the afternoon*,*... in the evening*, and *... at night*.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] *Rider's British Merlin* almanac for 1795 and a similar almanac for 1773 published in London used them.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Other than in English-speaking countries and some Spanish-speaking countries, the terms *a.m.* and *p.m.* are seldom used and often unknown.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In most countries, computers by default show the time in 24-hour notation.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Most operating systems, including Microsoft Windows and Unix-like systems such as Linux and macOS, activate the 12-hour notation by default for a limited number of language and region settings.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This behaviour can be changed by the user, such as with the Windows operating system's "Region and Language" settings.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The Latin abbreviations *a.m.* and *p.m.* (often written "am" and "pm", "AM" and "PM", or "A.M." and "P.M.") are used in English (and Spanish).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] When abbreviations and phrases are omitted, one may rely on sentence context and societal norms to reduce ambiguity.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] For example, if one commutes to work at "9:00", 9:00 a.m. may be implied, but if a social dance is scheduled to begin at "9:00", it may begin at 9:00 p.m.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The terms "a.m." and "p.m." are abbreviations of the Latin *ante meridiem* (before midday) and *post meridiem* (after midday).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Depending on the style guide referenced, the abbreviations "a.m." and "p.m." are variously written in small capitals ("am" and "pm"), uppercase letters without a period ("AM" and "PM"), uppercase letters with periods, or lowercase letters ("am" and "pm" or "a.m." and "p.m.").
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Some style guides suggest the use of a space between the number and the a.m. or p.m. abbreviation.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Style guides recommend not using a.m. and p.m. without a time preceding it.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The hour/minute separator varies between countries: some use a colon, others use a period (full stop), and still others use the letter h.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] (In some usages, particularly "military time", of the 24-hour clock, there is no separator between hours and minutes.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In speaking, it is common to round the time to the nearest five minutes and/or express the time as the past (or to) the closest hour; for example, "five past five" (5:05).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes *past* the hour means those minutes are added to the hour; "ten past five" means 5:10.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes *to, till* and *of* the hour mean those minutes are subtracted; "ten of five", "ten till five", and "ten to five" all mean 4:50.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Fifteen minutes is often called a *quarter hour*, and thirty minutes is often known as a *half hour*.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] For example, 5:15 can be phrased "(a) quarter past five" or "five-fifteen"; 5:30 can be "half past five", "five-thirty" or simply "half five".
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] The time 8:45 may be spoken as "eight forty-five" or "(a) quarter to nine".
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Polish, rounding off is mandatory when using (spoken) 12-hour clock, but disallowed when using 24 hour notation.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] 15:12 might be pronounced as "quarter past three" or "fifteen-twelve", but *not* "three-twelve" or "quarter past fifteen".
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In older English, it was common for the number 25 to be expressed as "five-and-twenty".
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In this way the time 8:35 might have been phrased as "five-and-twenty to 9", although this styling fell out of fashion in the later part of the 1900s and is now rarely used.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Instead of meaning 5:30, the "half five" expression is sometimes used to mean 4:30, or "halfway to five", especially for regions such as the American Midwest and other areas that have been particularly influenced by German culture.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This meaning follows the pattern choices of many Germanic and Slavic languages, including Serbo-Croatian, Dutch, Danish, Russian, Norwegian, and Swedish, as well as Hungarian, Finnish, and the languages of the Baltic States.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Moreover, in situations where the relevant hour is obvious or has been recently mentioned, a speaker might omit the hour and just say "quarter to (the hour)", "half past" or "ten till" to avoid an elaborate sentence in informal conversations.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] These forms are often commonly used in television and radio broadcasts that cover multiple time zones at one-hour intervals.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes may be expressed as an exact number of minutes past the hour specifying the time of day (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is "six thirty-two").
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Additionally, when expressing the time using the "past (after)" or "to (before)" formula, it is conventional to choose the number of minutes below 30 (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is conventionally "twenty-eight minutes to seven" rather than "thirty-two minutes past six").
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In spoken English, full hours are often represented by the numbered hour followed by *o'clock* (10:00 as *ten o'clock*, 2:00 as *two o'clock*).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] This may be followed by the "a.m." or "p.m." designator, though some phrases such as *in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening,* or *at night* more commonly follow analog-style terms such as *o'clock, half past three,* and *quarter to four.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] O'clock* itself may be omitted, telling a time as *four a.m.* or *four p.m.* Minutes ":01" to ":09" are usually pronounced as *oh one* to *oh nine* (*nought* or *zero* can also be used instead of *oh*).
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes ":10" to ":59" are pronounced as their usual number-words.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] For instance, 6:02 a.m. can be pronounced *six oh two a.m.* whereas 6:32 a.m. could be told as *six thirty-two a.m.*.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] It is not always clear what times "12:00 a.m." and "12:00 p.m." denote.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] In Latin, **ante meridiem** (a.m.) means "before midday" and **post meridiem** (p.m.) means "after midday".
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Since noon is neither before nor after itself, the terms a.m. and p.m. do not apply.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Although noon could be denoted "12 m.", this is seldom done and also does not resolve the question of how to indicate midnight.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] By convention, "12 a.m." denotes midnight and "12 p.m." denotes noon.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] However, many style guides recommend against using either because of the potential for confusion.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Many recommend instead using the unambiguous terms "12 noon" and "12 midnight", or simply "noon" and "midnight".
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] These include *The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language*, *The Canadian Press Stylebook*, and the NIST's "Frequently asked questions (FAQ)" web page.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Alternatively, some recommend referring to one minute before or after 12:00, especially when referring to midnight (for example, "11:59 p.m." or "12:01 a.m.").
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] These include the UK's National Physical Laboratory "FAQ-Time" web page.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] That has become common in the United States in legal contracts and for airplane, bus, or train schedules, though some schedules use other conventions.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Occasionally, when trains run at regular intervals, the pattern may be broken at midnight by displacing the midnight departure one or more minutes, such as to 11:59 p.m. or 12:01 a.m.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Some authors have been known to use the reverse of the normal convention.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Richards in his book *Mapping Time* (1999) provided a diagram in which 12 a.m. means noon and 12 p.m. means midnight.
[src:clock/12-hour-clock] Historically, the style manual of the United States Government Printing Office used 12 a.m. for noon and 12 p.m. for midnight, though this was reversed in its 2008 editions.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] The **180th meridian** or **antimeridian** is the meridian 180° both east and west of the prime meridian in a geographical coordinate system.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] The longitude at this line can be given as either east or west.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] On Earth, the prime and 180th meridians form a great ellipse that divides the planet into the Western and Eastern Hemispheres.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] The antimeridian passes mostly through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean but also runs across land in Russia, Fiji, and Antarctica.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] An important function of this meridian is its use as the basis for the International Date Line, which snakes around national borders to maintain date consistency within the territories of Russia, the United States, Kiribati, Fiji and New Zealand.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] The only places where roads cross this meridian are in Fiji and Russia.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] Fiji has several such roads and some buildings very close to it.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] Russia has three roads in the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] Many geographic software libraries or data formats project the world to a rectangle; very often this rectangle is split exactly at the 180th meridian.
[src:clock/180th-meridian] This often makes it non-trivial to do simple tasks (like representing an area, or a line) over the 180th meridian.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Clocks and watches with a **24-hour analog dial** have an hour hand that makes one complete revolution—360°—in a full day, or 24 hours per revolution.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In contrast, the more familiar 12-hour analog dial has an hour hand that completes two revolutions per day, or 12 hours per revolution.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Twenty-four-hour analog clocks and watches are commonly used by logistics workers, firefighters, police officers, paramedics, nurses, pilots, scientists, and military personnel.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] They are often preferred because they present an unambiguous representation of the entire day at once.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] This definition specifically refers to the use of a full circular dial to represent a 24-hour cycle.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Simply using numbers from 0 to 23 (or 1 to 24) is known as the *24-hour clock system*.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials also use 24-hour analog dials, as the shadow follows a path that repeats approximately once per day.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many sundials are marked with the double-XII (or double-12) system, where the numbers I to XII (or 1 to 12) appear twice—once for the morning and once for the afternoon and evening.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Thus, VI (6) appears twice on many sundial dials: once near sunrise and once near sunset.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Modern 24-hour analog dials—aside from sundials—are almost always marked with 24 numbers or hour markers around the edge, following the 24-hour clock system.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Because they display the entire day in one rotation, they do not require AM or PM indicators.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The ancient Egyptians divided the day into 24 hours.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] There are diagrams of circles divided into 24 sections in the astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senemut.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials use some or all of the 24-hour dial, because they show the position of the sun in the sky.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sometimes, for aesthetic rather than practical reasons, all the 24 hour marks are shown.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Medieval clocks often used the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by the widespread example of the astrolabe.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Northern Europe, the double-XII system was preferred: two sets of the Roman numerals I to XII were used, one on the left side for the night and morning hours, and another set on the right side of the dial to represent the afternoon and evening hours.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Italy, the numbers from 1 to 24 (I to XXIV in Roman numerals) were used, leading to the widespread use of the 24-hour system in that country.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] On Italian clocks, though, the I was often shown at the right side of the dial, rather than the top.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] This probably reflects the influence of the Italian timekeeping system, which started counting the hours of the day at sunset or twilight.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In northern Europe, the double-XII system was gradually superseded during the 14th and 15th centuries by the single-XII (12-hour system), leading to the widespread adoption of the 12-hour dial for popular use.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 24-hour analog dial continued to be used, but primarily by technicians, astronomers, scientists, and clockmakers.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] John Harrison, Thomas Tompion, and Mudge built a number of clocks with 24-hour analog dials, particularly when building astronomical and nautical instruments.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour dials were also used on sidereal clocks.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The famous Big Ben clock in London has a 24-hour dial as part of the mechanism, although it is not visible from the outside.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Astronauts used the 24-hour format due to the lack of day/night in the space environment.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 20th century, the 24-hour analog dial was adopted by radio amateurs, media, pilots, maritime, submariners, government, diplomats and for military use.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour analog watches and clocks are still being manufactured today, and are sought after by collectors and enthusiasts.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Manufacturers who make 24-hour analog watches include Glycine, Raketa, Vostok, Fortis, Poljot, Swatch, and many others.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A few rare variants place noon and midnight at the right and left sides.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] There is no ambiguity if the 24-hour numbering is used.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the United States, the government and military commonly use 24-hour clocks having noon at the bottom; the variant with noon at the top is far less common.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Multiple time zones can be displayed by having multiple hour hands or a rotating bezel.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel is a ring around the outside of the watch's face.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] When it is used, the top of the watch always represents midnight (or noon) GMT.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel, which also has hour markings, is then rotated so that its numbering represents local time.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] So, a pilot always has GMT time available for talking to air traffic control and, when they land, only has to rotate the bezel to "set" the watch to their new local time.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Glycine was the first to feature a 24-hour rotating bezel in 1953 with the Airman No.1 pilot watch.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The design became widely known when Rolex designed the Rolex GMT Master for Pan-Am pilots in 1954.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A 24-hour watch with a compass card dial can be used to determine direction when set to local noon and used in conjunction with the Sun.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many (but not all) digital watches can be set to show the time in 24-hour format.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A common use for the 24-hour analog method of representing time is for showing the way the time of day depends on one's location.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] George Orwell uses the 12-hour and 24-hour dials to symbolize the old and new worlds in his novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 12-hour dial is a relic of pre-revolutionary society, used to represent the desirable past; the 24-hour dial and time system is the compulsory standard imposed by the Party, and represents both conformity and the undesirable nature of the new world.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] It was a bright cold day in April, and the clocks were striking thirteen.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 1927 film *Metropolis*, the opening scene shows both a 24-hour analog clock and a 10-hour (decimal) analog clock, one above the other.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Both are used to convey the impression of an alien and highly efficient society.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Jules Verne's 1870 science fiction masterpiece *Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas*, Captain Nemo remarks that the clocks in the *Nautilus* use a 24-hour dial: "Now, look at that clock: it's electric, it runs with an accuracy rivaling the finest chronometers.
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] I've had it divided into twenty–four hours like Italian clocks, since neither day nor night, sun nor moon, exist for me, but only this artificial light that I import into the depths of the seas!
[src:clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A watch with a 24-hour analog dial is important to the resolution of Alfred Bester's 1953 short story "The Roller Coaster".
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The modern **24-hour clock** is the convention of timekeeping in which the day runs from midnight to midnight and is divided into 24 hours.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] This is indicated by the hours (and minutes) passed since midnight, from 00(:00) to 23(:59), with 24(:00) as an option to indicate the end of the day.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] This system, as opposed to the 12-hour clock, is the most commonly used time notation in the world today, and is used by the international standard ISO 8601.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] A number of countries, particularly English speaking, use the 12-hour clock, or a mixture of the 24- and 12-hour time systems.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In countries where the 12-hour clock is dominant, some professions prefer to use the 24-hour clock.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] For example, in the practice of medicine, the 24-hour clock is generally used in documentation of care as it prevents any ambiguity as to when events occurred in a patient's medical history.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] To indicate the exact end of the day, hh may take the value 24, with mm and ss taking the value 00.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In the case of a leap second, the value of ss may extend to 60.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] A leading zero is added for numbers under 10, but it is optional for the hours.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The leading zero is very commonly used in computer applications, and always used when a specification requires it (for example, ISO 8601).
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Where subsecond resolution is required, the seconds can be a decimal fraction; that is, the fractional part follows a decimal dot or comma, as in 01:23:45.678.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The most commonly used separator symbol between hours, minutes and seconds is the colon, which is also the symbol used in ISO 8601.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In the past, some European countries used the dot on the line as a separator, but most national standards on time notation have since then been changed to the international standard colon.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In some contexts (including some computer protocols and military time), no separator is used and times are written as, for example, "2359".
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In the 24-hour time notation, the day begins at midnight, 00:00 or 0:00, and the last minute of the day begins at 23:59.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In the ISO 8601 notation, 24:00 may also be used to refer to midnight at the end of a given date — that is, 24:00 of one day is the same time as 00:00 of the following day.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The notation 24:00 mainly serves to refer to the exact end of a day in a time interval.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] A typical usage is giving opening hours ending at midnight (e.g.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Similarly, some bus and train timetables show 00:00 as departure time and 24:00 as arrival time.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Legal contracts often run from the start date at 00:00 until the end date at 24:00.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] While the 24-hour notation unambiguously distinguishes between midnight at the start (00:00) and end (24:00) of any given date, there is no commonly accepted distinction among users of the 12-hour notation.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Style guides and military communication regulations in some English-speaking countries discourage the use of 24:00 even in the 24-hour notation, and recommend reporting times near midnight as 23:59 or 00:01 instead.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Sometimes the use of 00:00 is also avoided.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In variance with this, an older version of the correspondence manual for the United States Navy and United States Marine Corps specified 0001 to 2400.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The manual was updated in June 2015 to use 0000 to 2359.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Time-of-day notations beyond 24:00 (such as 24:01 or 25:00 instead of 00:01 or 01:00) are not commonly used and not covered by the relevant standards.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] However, they have been used occasionally in some special contexts in the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Canada, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, and China where business hours extend beyond midnight, such as broadcast television production and scheduling.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The GTFS public transport schedule listings file format has the concept of service days and expects times beyond 24:00 for trips that run after midnight.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] For example, Microsoft Windows and macOS activate the 12-hour notation by default only if a computer is in a handful of specific language and region settings.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The 24-hour system is commonly used in text-based interfaces.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] POSIX programs such as `ls` default to displaying timestamps in 24-hour format.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In the United States (a country which uses 12-hour clocks), the 24-hour clock is often referred to as *military time*.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] There is, however, a more specific standard for military time which refines the acceptable written and spoken forms of times on the 24-hour clock.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The first mechanical public clocks introduced in Italy were mechanical 24-hour clocks which counted the 24 hours of the day from one-half hour after sunset to the evening of the following day.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The 24th hour was the last hour of day time.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The modern 24-hour system is a late-19th century adaptation of the German midnight-starting system, and then prevailed in the world with the exception of some Anglophone countries.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Striking clocks had to produce 300 strokes each day, which required a lot of rope, and wore out the mechanism quickly, so some localities switched to ringing sequences of 1 to 12 twice, or 1 to 6 repeated four times.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Sandford Fleming, the engineer-in-chief of the Canadian Intercolonial Railway, was an early proponent of using the 24-hour clock as part of a programme to reform timekeeping, which also included establishing time zones and a standard prime meridian.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The Canadian Pacific Railway was among the first organisations to adopt the 24-hour clock, at midsummer 1886.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] A report by a government committee in the United Kingdom noted Italy as the first country among those mentioned to adopt 24-hour time nationally, in 1893.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Other European countries followed: France adopted it in 1912 (the French army in 1909), followed by Denmark (1916), and Greece (1917).
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] By 1920, Spain, Portugal, Belgium, and Switzerland had switched, followed by Turkey (1925), and Germany (1927).
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] By the early 1920s, many countries in Latin America had also adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] Some of the railways in India had switched before the outbreak of the war.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] During World War I, the British Royal Navy adopted the 24-hour clock in 1915, and the Allied armed forces followed soon after, with the British Army switching officially in 1918.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The Canadian armed forces first started to use the 24-hour clock in late 1917.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In 1920, the United States Navy was the first United States organisation to adopt the system; the United States Army, however, did not officially adopt the 24-hour clock until 1 July 1942.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The use of the 24-hour clock in the United Kingdom has grown steadily since the beginning of the 20th century, although attempts to make the system official failed more than once.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In 1934, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) switched to the 24-hour clock for broadcast announcements and programme listings.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] The experiment was halted after five months following a lack of enthusiasm from the public, and the BBC continued using the 12-hour clock.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In the same year, Pan American World Airways Corporation and Western Airlines in the United States both adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] In modern times, the BBC uses a mixture of both the 12-hour and the 24-hour clock.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] British Rail, London Transport, and the London Underground switched to the 24-hour clock for timetables in 1964.
[src:clock/24-hour-clock] A mixture of the 12- and 24-hour clocks similarly prevails in other English-speaking Commonwealth countries: French speakers have adopted the 24-hour clock in Canada much more broadly than English speakers, and Australia as well as New Zealand also use both systems.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A **clock** or **chronometer** is a device that measures and displays time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The clock is one of the oldest human inventions, meeting the need to measure intervals of time shorter than the natural units such as the day, the lunar month, and the year.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Devices operating on several physical processes have been used over the millennia.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some predecessors to the modern clock may be considered "clocks" that are based on movement in nature: A sundial shows the time by displaying the position of a shadow on a flat surface.
[src:clock/clock-p01] There is a range of duration timers, a well-known example being the hourglass.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Water clocks, along with sundials, are possibly the oldest time-measuring instruments.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A major advance occurred with the invention of the verge escapement, which made possible the first mechanical clocks around 1300 in Europe, which kept time with oscillating timekeepers like balance wheels.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Traditionally, in horology (the study of timekeeping), the term *clock* was used for a striking clock, while a clock that did not strike the hours audibly was called a **timepiece**.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This distinction is not generally made any longer.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Watches and other timepieces that can be carried on one's person are usually not referred to as clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Spring-driven clocks appeared during the 15th century.
[src:clock/clock-p01] During the 15th and 16th centuries, clockmaking flourished.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The next development in accuracy occurred after 1656 with the invention of the pendulum clock by Christiaan Huygens.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A major stimulus to improving the accuracy and reliability of clocks was the importance of precise time-keeping for navigation.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The mechanism of a timepiece with a series of gears driven by a spring or weights is referred to as clockwork; the term is used by extension for a similar mechanism not used in a timepiece.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The electric clock was patented in 1840, and electronic clocks were introduced in the 20th century, becoming widespread with the development of small battery-powered semiconductor devices.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The timekeeping element in every modern clock is a harmonic oscillator, a physical object (resonator) that vibrates or oscillates at a particular frequency.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This object can be a pendulum, a balance wheel, a tuning fork, a quartz crystal, or the vibration of electrons in atoms as they emit microwaves, the last of which is so precise that it serves as the formal definition of the second.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks have different ways of displaying the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Analog clocks indicate time with a traditional clock face and moving hands.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Digital clocks display a numeric representation of time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Two numbering systems are in use: 12-hour time notation and 24-hour notation.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Most digital clocks use electronic mechanisms and LCD, LED, or VFD displays.
[src:clock/clock-p01] For the blind and for use over telephones, speaking clocks state the time audibly in words.
[src:clock/clock-p01] There are also clocks for the blind that have displays that can be read by touch.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The word *clock* derives from the medieval Latin word for 'bell'—*clocca*—and has cognates in many European languages.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks spread to England from the Low Countries, so the English word came from the Middle Low German and Middle Dutch *Klocke*.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The word is also derived from the Middle English *clokke*, Old North French *cloque*, or Middle Dutch *clocke*, all of which mean 'bell'.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The apparent position of the Sun in the sky changes over the course of each day, reflecting the rotation of the Earth.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Shadows cast by stationary objects move correspondingly, so their positions can be used to indicate the time of day.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A sundial shows the time by displaying the position of a shadow on a (usually) flat surface that has markings that correspond to the hours.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Sundials can be horizontal, vertical, or in other orientations.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Sundials were widely used in ancient times.
[src:clock/clock-p01] With knowledge of latitude, a well-constructed sundial can measure local solar time with reasonable accuracy, within a minute or two.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Sundials continued to be used to monitor the performance of clocks until the 1830s, when the use of the telegraph and trains standardized time and time zones between cities.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Many devices can be used to mark the passage of time without respect to reference time (time of day, hours, minutes, etc.) and can be useful for measuring duration or intervals.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Examples of such duration timers are candle clocks, incense clocks, and the hourglass.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Both the candle clock and the incense clock work on the same principle, wherein the consumption of resources is more or less constant, allowing reasonably precise and repeatable estimates of time passages.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In the hourglass, fine sand pouring through a tiny hole at a constant rate indicates an arbitrary, predetermined passage of time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The resource is not consumed, but re-used.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Water clocks, along with sundials, are possibly the oldest time-measuring instruments, with the only exception being the day-counting tally stick.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Given their great antiquity, where and when they first existed is not known and is perhaps unknowable.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The bowl-shaped outflow is the simplest form of a water clock and is known to have existed in Babylon and Egypt around the 16th century BC.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Other regions of the world, including India and China, also have early evidence of water clocks, but the earliest dates are less certain.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some authors, however, write about water clocks appearing as early as 4000 BC in these regions of the world.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Macedonian astronomer Andronicus of Cyrrhus supervised the construction of the Tower of the Winds in Athens in the 1st century BC, which housed a large clepsydra inside as well as multiple prominent sundials outside, allowing it to function as a kind of early clocktower.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Greek and Roman civilizations advanced water clock design with improved accuracy.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These advances were passed on through Byzantine and Islamic times, eventually making their way back to Europe.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Independently, the Chinese developed their own advanced water clocks (水鐘) by 725 AD, passing their ideas on to Korea and Japan.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some water clock designs were developed independently, and some knowledge was transferred through the spread of trade.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Pre-modern societies do not have the same precise timekeeping requirements that exist in modern industrial societies, where every hour of work or rest is monitored and work may start or finish at any time regardless of external conditions.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Instead, water clocks in ancient societies were used mainly for astrological reasons.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These early water clocks were calibrated with a sundial.
[src:clock/clock-p01] While never reaching the level of accuracy of a modern timepiece, the water clock was the most accurate and commonly used timekeeping device for millennia until it was replaced by the more accurate pendulum clock in 17th-century Europe.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Islamic civilization is credited with further advancing the accuracy of clocks through elaborate engineering.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 797 (or possibly 801), the Abbasid caliph of Baghdad, Harun al-Rashid, presented Charlemagne with an Asian elephant named Abul-Abbas together with a "particularly elaborate example" of a water clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Pope Sylvester II introduced clocks to northern and western Europe around 1000 AD.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The first known geared clock was invented by the great mathematician, physicist, and engineer Archimedes during the 3rd century BC.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Archimedes created his astronomical clock, which was also a cuckoo clock with birds singing and moving every hour.
[src:clock/clock-p01] It is the first carillon clock as it plays music simultaneously with a person blinking his eyes, surprised by the singing birds.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Archimedes clock works with a system of four weights, counterweights, and strings regulated by a system of floats in a water container with siphons that regulate the automatic continuation of the clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The principles of this type of clock are described by the mathematician and physicist Hero, who says that some of them work with a chain that turns a gear in the mechanism.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Another Greek clock probably constructed at the time of Alexander was in Gaza, as described by Procopius.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Gaza clock was probably a Meteoroskopeion, i.e., a building showing celestial phenomena and the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] It had a pointer for the time and some automations similar to the Archimedes clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] There were 12 doors opening one every hour, with Hercules performing his labors, the Lion at one o'clock, etc., and at night a lamp becomes visible every hour, with 12 windows opening to show the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Tang dynasty Buddhist monk Yi Xing along with government official Liang Lingzan made the escapement in 723 (or 725) to the workings of a water-powered armillary sphere and clock drive, which was the world's first clockwork escapement.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Song dynasty polymath and genius Su Song (1020–1101) incorporated it into his monumental innovation of the astronomical clock tower of Kaifeng in 1088.
[src:clock/clock-p01] His astronomical clock and rotating armillary sphere still relied on the use of either flowing water during the spring, summer, and autumn seasons or liquid mercury during the freezing temperatures of winter (i.e., hydraulics).
[src:clock/clock-p01] In Su Song's waterwheel linkwork device, the action of the escapement's arrest and release was achieved by gravity exerted periodically as the continuous flow of liquid-filled containers of a limited size.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In a single line of evolution, Su Song's clock therefore united the concepts of the clepsydra and the mechanical clock into one device run by mechanics and hydraulics.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Song was also strongly influenced by the earlier armillary sphere created by Zhang Sixun (976 AD), who also employed the escapement mechanism and used liquid mercury instead of water in the waterwheel of his astronomical clock tower.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The mechanical clockworks for Su Song's astronomical tower featured a great driving-wheel that was 11 feet in diameter, carrying 36 scoops, into each of which water was poured at a uniform rate from the "constant-level tank".
[src:clock/clock-p01] The main driving shaft of iron, with its cylindrical necks supported on iron crescent-shaped bearings, ended in a pinion, which engaged a gear wheel at the lower end of the main vertical transmission shaft.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This great astronomical hydromechanical clock tower was about ten metres high (about 30 feet), featured a clock escapement, and was indirectly powered by a rotating wheel either with falling water or liquid mercury.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A full-sized working replica of Su Song's clock exists in the Republic of China (Taiwan)'s National Museum of Natural Science, Taichung city.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This full-scale, fully functional replica, approximately 12 meters (39 feet) in height, was constructed from Su Song's original descriptions and mechanical drawings.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Chinese escapement spread west and was the source for Western escapement technology.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In the 12th century, Al-Jazari, an engineer from Mesopotamia (lived 1136–1206) who worked for the Artuqid king of Diyar-Bakr, Nasir al-Din, made numerous clocks of all shapes and sizes.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The most reputed clocks included the elephant, scribe, and castle clocks, some of which have been successfully reconstructed.
[src:clock/clock-p01] As well as telling the time, these grand clocks were symbols of the status, grandeur, and wealth of the Urtuq State.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Knowledge of these mercury escapements may have spread through Europe with translations of Arabic and Spanish texts.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The word *horologia* (from the Greek ὥρα—'hour', and λέγειν—'to tell') was used to describe early mechanical clocks, but the use of this word (still used in several Romance languages) for all timekeepers conceals the true nature of the mechanisms.
[src:clock/clock-p01] For example, there is a record that in 1176, Sens Cathedral in France installed an 'horologe', but the mechanism used is unknown.
[src:clock/clock-p01] According to Jocelyn de Brakelond, in 1198, during a fire at the abbey of St Edmundsbury (now Bury St Edmunds), the monks "ran to the clock" to fetch water, indicating that their water clock had a reservoir large enough to help extinguish the occasional fire.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The word *clock* (via Medieval Latin *clocca* from Old Irish *clocc*, both meaning 'bell'), which gradually supersedes "horologe", suggests that it was the sound of bells that also characterized the prototype mechanical clocks that appeared during the 13th century in Europe.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In Europe, between 1280 and 1320, there was an increase in the number of references to clocks and horologes in church records, and this probably indicates that a new type of clock mechanism had been devised.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Existing clock mechanisms that used water power were being adapted to take their driving power from falling weights.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This power was controlled by some form of oscillating mechanism, probably derived from existing bell-ringing or alarm devices.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This controlled release of power – the escapement – marks the beginning of the true mechanical clock, which differed from the previously mentioned cogwheel clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The verge escapement mechanism appeared during the surge of true mechanical clock development, which did not need any kind of fluid power, like water or mercury, to work.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These mechanical clocks were intended for two main purposes: for signalling and notification (e.g., the timing of services and public events) and for modeling the Solar System.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The former purpose is administrative; the latter arises naturally given the scholarly interests in astronomy, science, and astrology and how these subjects integrated with the religious philosophy of the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The astrolabe was used both by astronomers and astrologers, and it was natural to apply a clockwork drive to the rotating plate to produce a working model of the solar system.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Simple clocks intended mainly for notification were installed in towers and did not always require faces or hands.
[src:clock/clock-p01] They would have announced the canonical hours or intervals between set times of prayer.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Canonical hours varied in length as the times of sunrise and sunset shifted.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The more sophisticated astronomical clocks would have had moving dials or hands and would have shown the time in various time systems, including Italian hours, canonical hours, and time as measured by astronomers at the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Both styles of clocks started acquiring extravagant features, such as automata.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1283, a large clock was installed at Dunstable Priory in Bedfordshire in southern England; its location above the rood screen suggests that it was not a water clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1292, Canterbury Cathedral installed a 'great horloge'.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Over the next 30 years, there were mentions of clocks at a number of ecclesiastical institutions in England, Italy, and France.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1322, a new clock was installed in Norwich, an expensive replacement for an earlier clock installed in 1273.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This had a large (2 metre) astronomical dial with automata and bells.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The costs of the installation included the full-time employment of two clockkeepers for two years.
[src:clock/clock-p01] An elaborate water clock, the 'Cosmic Engine', was invented by Su Song, a Chinese polymath, designed and constructed in China in 1092.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This great astronomical hydromechanical clock tower was about ten metres high (about 30 feet) and was indirectly powered by a rotating wheel with falling water and liquid mercury, which turned an armillary sphere capable of calculating complex astronomical problems.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In Europe, there were the clocks constructed by Richard of Wallingford in Albans by 1336, and by Giovanni de Dondi in Padua from 1348 to 1364.
[src:clock/clock-p01] They no longer exist, but detailed descriptions of their design and construction survive, and modern reproductions have been made.
[src:clock/clock-p01] They illustrate how quickly the theory of the mechanical clock had been translated into practical constructions, and also that one of the many impulses to their development had been the desire of astronomers to investigate celestial phenomena.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Astrarium of Giovanni Dondi dell'Orologio was a complex astronomical clock built between 1348 and 1364 in Padua, Italy, by the doctor and clock-maker Giovanni Dondi dell'Orologio.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Astrarium had seven faces and 107 moving gears; it showed the positions of the Sun, the Moon and the five planets then known, as well as religious feast days.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The astrarium stood about 1 metre high, and consisted of a seven-sided brass or iron framework resting on 7 decorative paw-shaped feet.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The lower section provided a 24-hour dial and a large calendar drum, showing the fixed feasts of the church, the movable feasts, and the position in the zodiac of the Moon's ascending node.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The upper section contained 7 dials, each about 30 cm in diameter, showing the positional data for the Primum Mobile, Venus, Mercury, the Moon, Saturn, Jupiter, and Mars.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Directly above the 24-hour dial is the dial of the Primum Mobile, so called because it reproduces the diurnal motion of the stars and the annual motion of the Sun against the background of stars.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Each of the 'planetary' dials used complex clockwork to produce reasonably accurate models of the planets' motion.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These agreed reasonably well both with Ptolemaic theory and with observations.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Wallingford's clock had a large astrolabe-type dial, showing the Sun, the Moon's age, phase, and node, a star map, and possibly the planets.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In addition, it had a wheel of fortune and an indicator of the state of the tide at London Bridge.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Bells rang every hour, the number of strokes indicating the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Dondi's clock was a seven-sided construction, 1 metre high, with dials showing the time of day, including minutes, the motions of all the known planets, an automatic calendar of fixed and movable feasts, and an eclipse prediction hand rotating once every 18 years.
[src:clock/clock-p01] It is not known how accurate or reliable these clocks would have been.
[src:clock/clock-p01] They were probably adjusted manually every day to compensate for errors caused by wear and imprecise manufacture.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Water clocks are sometimes still used, and can be examined in places such as ancient castles and museums.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The Salisbury Cathedral clock, built in 1386, is considered to be the world's oldest surviving mechanical clock that strikes the hours.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clockmakers developed their art in various ways.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Building smaller clocks was a technical challenge, as was improving accuracy and reliability.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks could be impressive showpieces to demonstrate skilled craftsmanship, or less expensive, mass-produced items for domestic use.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The escapement in particular was an important factor affecting the clock's accuracy, so many different mechanisms were tried.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Spring-driven clocks appeared during the 15th century, although they are often erroneously credited to Nuremberg watchmaker Peter Henlein (or Henle, or Hele) around 1511.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The earliest existing spring driven clock is the chamber clock given to Phillip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, around 1430, now in the Germanisches Nationalmuseum.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Spring power presented clockmakers with a new problem: how to keep the clock movement running at a constant rate as the spring ran down.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This resulted in the invention of the *stackfreed* and the fusee in the 15th century, and many other innovations, down to the invention of the modern *going barrel* in 1760.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Early clock dials did not indicate minutes and seconds.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A clock with a dial indicating minutes was illustrated in a 1475 manuscript by Paulus Almanus, and some 15th-century clocks in Germany indicated minutes and seconds.
[src:clock/clock-p01] An early record of a seconds hand on a clock dates back to about 1560 on a clock now in the Fremersdorf collection.
[src:clock/clock-p01] During the 15th and 16th centuries, clockmaking flourished, particularly in the metalworking towns of Nuremberg and Augsburg, and in Blois, France.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some of the more basic table clocks have only one time-keeping hand, with the dial between the hour markers being divided into four equal parts making the clocks readable to the nearest 15 minutes.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Other clocks were exhibitions of craftsmanship and skill, incorporating astronomical indicators and musical movements.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The cross-beat escapement was invented in 1584 by Jost Bürgi, who also developed the remontoire.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Bürgi's clocks were a great improvement in accuracy as they were correct to within a minute a day.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These clocks helped the 16th-century astronomer Tycho Brahe to observe astronomical events with much greater precision than before.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The next development in accuracy occurred after 1656 with the invention of the pendulum clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Galileo had the idea to use a swinging bob to regulate the motion of a time-telling device earlier in the 17th century.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Christiaan Huygens, however, is usually credited as the inventor.
[src:clock/clock-p01] He determined the mathematical formula that related pendulum length to time (about 99.4 cm or 39.1 inches for the one second movement) and had the first pendulum-driven clock made.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The first model clock was built in 1657 in the Hague, but it was in England that the idea was taken up.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The longcase clock (also known as the *grandfather clock*) was created to house the pendulum and works by the English clockmaker William Clement in 1670 or 1671.
[src:clock/clock-p01] It was also at this time that clock cases began to be made of wood and clock faces to use enamel as well as hand-painted ceramics.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1670, William Clement created the anchor escapement, an improvement over Huygens' crown escapement.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clement also introduced the pendulum suspension spring in 1671.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The concentric minute hand was added to the clock by Daniel Quare, a London clockmaker and others, and the second hand was first introduced.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1675, Huygens and Robert Hooke invented the spiral balance spring, or the hairspring, designed to control the oscillating speed of the balance wheel.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This crucial advance finally made accurate pocket watches possible.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The great English clockmaker Thomas Tompion, was one of the first to use this mechanism successfully in his pocket watches, and he adopted the minute hand which, after a variety of designs were trialled, eventually stabilised into the modern-day configuration.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The rack and snail striking mechanism for striking clocks, was introduced during the 17th century and had distinct advantages over the 'countwheel' (or 'locking plate') mechanism.
[src:clock/clock-p01] During the 20th century there was a common misconception that Edward Barlow invented *rack and snail* striking.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In fact, his invention was connected with a repeating mechanism employing the rack and snail.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The repeating clock, that chimes the number of hours (or even minutes) on demand was invented by either Quare or Barlow in 1676.
[src:clock/clock-p01] George Graham invented the deadbeat escapement for clocks in 1720.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The position of a ship at sea could be determined with reasonable accuracy if a navigator could refer to a clock that lost or gained less than about 10 seconds per day.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This clock could not contain a pendulum, which would be virtually useless on a rocking ship.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1714, the British government offered large financial rewards to the value of 20,000 pounds for anyone who could determine longitude accurately.
[src:clock/clock-p01] John Harrison, who dedicated his life to improving the accuracy of his clocks, later received considerable sums under the Longitude Act.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1735, Harrison built his first chronometer, which he steadily improved on over the next thirty years before submitting it for examination.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The clock had many innovations, including the use of bearings to reduce friction, weighted balances to compensate for the ship's pitch and roll in the sea and the use of two different metals to reduce the problem of expansion from heat.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The chronometer was tested in 1761 by Harrison's son and by the end of 10 weeks the clock was in error by less than 5 seconds.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The British had dominated watch manufacture for much of the 17th and 18th centuries, but maintained a system of production that was geared towards high quality products for the elite.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Although there was an attempt to modernise clock manufacture with mass-production techniques and the application of duplicating tools and machinery by the British Watch Company in 1843, it was in the United States that this system took off.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1816, Eli Terry and some other Connecticut clockmakers developed a way of mass-producing clocks by using interchangeable parts.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Aaron Lufkin Dennison started a factory in 1851 in Massachusetts that also used interchangeable parts, and by 1861 was running a successful enterprise incorporated as the Waltham Watch Company.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1815, the English scientist Francis Ronalds published the first electric clock powered by dry pile batteries.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Alexander Bain, a Scottish clockmaker, patented the electric clock in 1840.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The electric clock's mainspring is wound either with an electric motor or with an electromagnet and armature.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1841, he first patented the electromagnetic pendulum.
[src:clock/clock-p01] By the end of the nineteenth century, the advent of the dry cell battery made it feasible to use electric power in clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Spring or weight-driven clocks that use electricity, either alternating current (AC) or direct current (DC), to rewind the spring or raise the weight of a mechanical clock would be classified as an electromechanical clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This classification would also apply to clocks that employ an electrical impulse to propel the pendulum.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In electromechanical clocks, electricity serves no time-keeping function.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These types of clocks were made as individual timepieces but are more commonly used in synchronized time installations in schools, businesses, factories, railroads and government facilities as a master clock and slave clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Where an AC electrical supply of stable frequency is available, timekeeping can be maintained very reliably by using a synchronous motor, essentially counting the cycles.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The supply current alternates with an accurate frequency of 50 hertz in many countries, and 60 hertz in others.
[src:clock/clock-p01] While the frequency may vary slightly during the day as the load changes, generators are designed to maintain an accurate number of cycles over a day, so the clock may be a fraction of a second slow or fast at any time, but will be perfectly accurate over a long time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The rotor of the motor rotates at a speed that is related to the alternation frequency.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Appropriate gearing converts this rotation speed to the correct ones for the hands of the analog clock.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Time in these cases is measured in several ways, such as by counting the cycles of the AC supply, vibration of a tuning fork, the behaviour of quartz crystals, or the quantum vibrations of atoms.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Electronic circuits divide these high-frequency oscillations into slower ones that drive the time display.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The piezoelectric properties of crystalline quartz were discovered by Jacques and Pierre Curie in 1880.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The first crystal oscillator was invented in 1917 by Alexander M.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Nicolson, after which the first quartz crystal oscillator was built by Walter G.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1927 the first quartz clock was built by Warren Marrison and J.W.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Horton at Bell Telephone Laboratories in Canada.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The following decades saw the development of quartz clocks as precision time measurement devices in laboratory settings—the bulky and delicate counting electronics, built with vacuum tubes at the time, limited their practical use elsewhere.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The National Bureau of Standards (now NIST) based the time standard of the United States on quartz clocks from late 1929 until the 1960s, when it changed to atomic clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In 1969, Seiko produced the world's first quartz wristwatch, the Astron.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Their inherent accuracy and low cost of production resulted in the subsequent proliferation of quartz clocks and watches.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Currently, atomic clocks are the most accurate clocks in existence.
[src:clock/clock-p01] They are considerably more accurate than quartz clocks as they can be accurate to within a few seconds over trillions of years.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Atomic clocks were first theorized by Lord Kelvin in 1879.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In the 1930s the development of magnetic resonance created practical method for doing this.
[src:clock/clock-p01] A prototype ammonia maser device was built in 1949 at the U.S.
[src:clock/clock-p01] National Bureau of Standards (NBS, now NIST).
[src:clock/clock-p01] Although it was less accurate than existing quartz clocks, it served to demonstrate the concept.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The first accurate atomic clock, a caesium standard based on a certain transition of the caesium-133 atom, was built by Louis Essen in 1955 at the National Physical Laboratory in the UK.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Calibration of the caesium standard atomic clock was carried out by the use of the astronomical time scale *ephemeris time* (ET).
[src:clock/clock-p01] As of 2013, the most stable atomic clocks are ytterbium clocks, which are stable to within less than two parts in 1 quintillion (2×10−18).
[src:clock/clock-p01] Although the mechanisms they use vary, all oscillating clocks, mechanical, electric, and atomic, work similarly and can be divided into analogous parts.
[src:clock/clock-p01] They consist of an object that repeats the same motion over and over again, an *oscillator*, with a precisely constant time interval between each repetition, or 'beat'.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Attached to the oscillator is a *controller* device, which sustains the oscillator's motion by replacing the energy it loses to friction, and converts its oscillations into a series of pulses.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The pulses are then counted by some type of *counter*, and the number of counts is converted into convenient units, usually seconds, minutes, hours, etc.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Finally some kind of *indicator* displays the result in human readable form.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The timekeeping element in every modern clock is a harmonic oscillator, a physical object (resonator) that vibrates or oscillates repetitively at a precisely constant frequency.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The advantage of a harmonic oscillator over other forms of oscillator is that it employs resonance to vibrate at a precise natural resonant frequency or "beat" dependent only on its physical characteristics, and resists vibrating at other rates.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The possible precision achievable by a harmonic oscillator is measured by a parameter called its Q, or quality factor, which increases (other things being equal) with its resonant frequency.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This is why there has been a long-term trend toward higher frequency oscillators in clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Balance wheels and pendulums always include a means of adjusting the rate of the timepiece.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Quartz timepieces sometimes include a rate screw that adjusts a capacitor for that purpose.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Atomic clocks are primary standards, and their rate cannot be adjusted.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This has the dual function of keeping the oscillator running by giving it 'pushes' to replace the energy lost to friction, and converting its vibrations into a series of pulses that serve to measure the time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] In mechanical clocks, the low Q of the balance wheel or pendulum oscillator made them very sensitive to the disturbing effect of the impulses of the escapement, so the escapement had a great effect on the accuracy of the clock, and many escapement designs were tried.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The higher Q of resonators in electronic clocks makes them relatively insensitive to the disturbing effects of the drive power, so the driving oscillator circuit is a much less critical component.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This counts the pulses and adds them up to get traditional time units of seconds, minutes, hours, etc.
[src:clock/clock-p01] It usually has a provision for *setting* the clock by manually entering the correct time into the counter.
[src:clock/clock-p01] This displays the count of seconds, minutes, hours, etc. in a human readable form.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks can be classified by the type of time display, as well as by the method of timekeeping.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Analog clocks usually use a clock face which indicates time using rotating pointers called "hands" on a fixed numbered dial or dials.
[src:clock/clock-p01] It may also have a "second hand" which indicates the seconds in the current minute.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The only other widely used clock face today is the 24 hour analog dial, because of the use of 24 hour time in military organizations and timetables.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Before the modern clock face was standardized during the Industrial Revolution, many other face designs were used throughout the years, including dials divided into 6, 8, 10, and 24 hours.
[src:clock/clock-p01] During the French Revolution the French government tried to introduce a 10-hour clock, as part of their decimal-based metric system of measurement, but it did not achieve widespread use.
[src:clock/clock-p01] An Italian 6 hour clock was developed in the 18th century, presumably to save power (a clock or watch striking 24 times uses more power).
[src:clock/clock-p01] Another type of analog clock is the sundial, which tracks the sun continuously, registering the time by the shadow position of its gnomon.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Because the sun does not adjust to daylight saving time, users must add an hour during that time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Corrections must also be made for the equation of time, and for the difference between the longitudes of the sundial and of the central meridian of the time zone that is being used (i.e.
[src:clock/clock-p01] 15 degrees east of the prime meridian for each hour that the time zone is ahead of GMT).
[src:clock/clock-p01] Sundials use some or part of the 24 hour analog dial.
[src:clock/clock-p01] There also exist clocks which use a digital display despite having an analog mechanism—these are commonly referred to as flip clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] For example, the "Twelv" clock indicates the current hour using one of twelve colors, and indicates the minute by showing a proportion of a circular disk, similar to a moon phase.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Most digital clocks use electronic mechanisms and LCD, LED, or VFD displays; many other display technologies are used as well (cathode ray tubes, nixie tubes, etc.).
[src:clock/clock-p01] After a reset, battery change or power failure, these clocks without a backup battery or capacitor either start counting from 12:00, or stay at 12:00, often with blinking digits indicating that the time needs to be set.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some newer clocks will reset themselves based on radio or Internet time servers that are tuned to national atomic clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Since the introduction of digital clocks in the 1960s, there has been a notable decline in the use of analog clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some clocks, called 'flip clocks', have digital displays that work mechanically.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The digits are painted on sheets of material which are mounted like the pages of a book.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Once a minute, a page is turned over to reveal the next digit.
[src:clock/clock-p01] These displays are usually easier to read in brightly lit conditions than LCDs or LEDs.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Also, they do not go back to 12:00 after a power interruption.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Flip clocks generally do not have electronic mechanisms.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Usually, they are driven by AC-synchronous motors.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks with analog quadrants, with a digital component, usually minutes and hours displayed analogously and seconds displayed in digital mode.
[src:clock/clock-p01] For convenience, distance, telephony or blindness, auditory clocks present the time as sounds.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The sound is either spoken natural language, (e.g.
[src:clock/clock-p01] "The time is twelve thirty-five"), or as auditory codes (e.g. number of sequential bell rings on the hour represents the number of the hour like the bell, Big Ben).
[src:clock/clock-p01] Most telecommunication companies also provide a speaking clock service as well.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Word clocks are clocks that display the time visually using sentences.
[src:clock/clock-p01] E.g.: "It's about three o'clock." These clocks can be implemented in hardware or software.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some clocks, usually digital ones, include an optical projector that shines a magnified image of the time display onto a screen or onto a surface such as an indoor ceiling or wall.
[src:clock/clock-p01] The digits are large enough to be easily read, without using glasses, by persons with moderately imperfect vision, so the clocks are convenient for use in their bedrooms.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Usually, the timekeeping circuitry has a battery as a backup source for an uninterrupted power supply to keep the clock on time, while the projection light only works when the unit is connected to an A.C. supply.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Completely battery-powered portable versions resembling flashlights are also available.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Auditory and projection clocks can be used by people who are blind or have limited vision.
[src:clock/clock-p01] There are also clocks for the blind that have displays that can be read by using the sense of touch.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some of these are similar to normal analog displays, but are constructed so the hands can be felt without damaging them.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Another type is essentially digital, and uses devices that use a code such as Braille to show the digits so that they can be felt with the fingertips.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some clocks have several displays driven by a single mechanism, and some others have several completely separate mechanisms in a single case.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks in public places often have several faces visible from different directions, so that the clock can be read from anywhere in the vicinity; all the faces show the same time.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Other clocks show the current time in several time-zones.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Watches that are intended to be carried by travellers often have two displays, one for the local time and the other for the time at home, which is useful for making pre-arranged phone calls.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some equation clocks have two displays, one showing mean time and the other solar time, as would be shown by a sundial.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Some clocks have both analog and digital displays.
[src:clock/clock-p01] Clocks with Braille displays usually also have conventional digits so they can be read by sighted people.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Clocks are in homes, offices and many other places; smaller ones (watches) are carried on the wrist or in a pocket; larger ones are in public places, e.g. a railway station or church.
[src:clock/clock-p02] A small clock is often shown in a corner of computer displays, mobile phones and many MP3 players.
[src:clock/clock-p02] The primary purpose of a clock is to *display* the time.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Clocks may also have the facility to make a loud alert signal at a specified time, typically to waken a sleeper at a preset time; they are referred to as *alarm clocks*.
[src:clock/clock-p02] The alarm may start at a low volume and become louder, or have the facility to be switched off for a few minutes then resume.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Alarm clocks with visible indicators are sometimes used to indicate to children too young to read the time that the time for sleep has finished; they are sometimes called *training clocks*.
[src:clock/clock-p02] A clock mechanism may be used to *control* a device according to time, e.g. a central heating system, a VCR, or a time bomb (see: digital counter).
[src:clock/clock-p02] Such mechanisms are usually called timers.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Clock mechanisms are also used to drive devices such as solar trackers and astronomical telescopes, which have to turn at accurately controlled speeds to counteract the rotation of the Earth.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Most digital computers depend on an internal signal at constant frequency to synchronize processing; this is referred to as a clock signal.
[src:clock/clock-p02] (A few research projects are developing CPUs based on asynchronous circuits.) Some equipment, including computers, also maintains time and date for use as required; this is referred to as time-of-day clock, and is distinct from the system clock signal, although possibly based on counting its cycles.
[src:clock/clock-p02] For some scientific work timing of the utmost accuracy is essential.
[src:clock/clock-p02] It is also necessary to have a standard of the maximum accuracy against which working clocks can be calibrated.
[src:clock/clock-p02] An ideal clock would give the time to unlimited accuracy, but this is not realisable.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Many physical processes, in particular including some transitions between atomic energy levels, occur at exceedingly stable frequency; counting cycles of such a process can give a very accurate and consistent time—clocks which work this way are usually called atomic clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Such clocks are typically large, very expensive, require a controlled environment, and are far more accurate than required for most purposes; they are typically used in a standards laboratory.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Until advances in the late twentieth century, navigation depended on the ability to measure latitude and longitude.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Latitude can be determined through celestial navigation; the measurement of longitude requires accurate knowledge of time.
[src:clock/clock-p02] This need was a major motivation for the development of accurate mechanical clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p02] John Harrison created the first highly accurate marine chronometer in the mid-18th century.
[src:clock/clock-p02] The Noon gun in Cape Town still fires an accurate signal to allow ships to check their chronometers.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Many buildings near major ports used to have (some still do) a large ball mounted on a tower or mast arranged to drop at a pre-determined time, for the same purpose.
[src:clock/clock-p02] While satellite navigation systems such as GPS require unprecedentedly accurate knowledge of time, this is supplied by equipment on the satellites; vehicles no longer need timekeeping equipment.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Clocks can be used to measure varying periods of time in games and sports.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Stopwatches can be used to time the performance of track athletes.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Chess clocks are used to limit the board game players' time to make a move.
[src:clock/clock-p02] In various sports, *game clocks* measure the duration the game or subdivisions of the game, while other clocks may be used for tracking different durations; these include play clocks, shot clocks, and pitch clocks.
[src:clock/clock-p02] In the United Kingdom, clocks are associated with various beliefs, many involving death or bad luck.
[src:clock/clock-p02] In legends, clocks have reportedly stopped of their own accord upon a nearby person's death, especially those of monarchs.
[src:clock/clock-p02] The clock in the House of Lords supposedly stopped at "nearly" the hour of George III's death in 1820, the one at Balmoral Castle stopped during the hour of Queen Victoria's death, and similar legends are related about clocks associated with William IV and Elizabeth I.
[src:clock/clock-p02] One stopping before a person has died may foretell coming death.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Similarly, if a clock strikes during a church hymn or a marriage ceremony, death or calamity is prefigured for the parishioners or a spouse, respectively.
[src:clock/clock-p02] Death or ill events are foreshadowed if a clock strikes the wrong time.
[src:clock/clock-p02] It may also be unlucky to have a clock face a fire or to speak while a clock is striking.
[src:clock/clock-p02] In Chinese culture, giving a clock (traditional Chinese: 送鐘; simplified Chinese: 送钟; pinyin: *sòng zhōng*) is often taboo, especially to the elderly, as it is a homophone of the act of attending another's funeral (traditional Chinese: 送終; simplified Chinese: 送终; pinyin: *sòngzhōng*).
